declarations.comments:
An amount of money in the smallest discrete unit of a particular currency.
For example, `wrap 256 :: Discrete GBP` would represent £2.56, whereas
`wrap 256 :: Discrete JPY` would represent ¥256. If you want to work with
higher granularity, you can define your own currency type.
declarations.title: Discrete

declarations.comments: Apply a format to a discrete amount.
declarations.title: formatDiscrete

declarations.comments:
DEPRECATED: use `formatDiscrete` instead.

Show the discrete value with the correct number of decimals. Will not
prepend the currency sign. Negative amounts are prefixed with a
hyphen-minus.

Examples:

 - `showDiscrete (Discrete   256  :: Discrete GBP) ==  "2.56"`
 - `showDiscrete (Discrete (-256) :: Discrete GBP) == "-2.56"`
declarations.title: showDiscrete

declarations.comments: Part of a format specification for amounts.
declarations.title: FormatF

declarations.comments: Perform a format only if the amount is negative.
declarations.title: ifNegative

declarations.comments: Insert the absolute value of the amount in decimal.
declarations.title: absolute

declarations.comments:
Utility function so you can define formats with do notation. For example:

```purescript
myFormat = do
  ifNegative $ literal "("
  currencyCode
  literal space
  amount
  ifNegative $ literal ")"
  where bind = sbind
```
declarations.title: sbind

declarations.comments:
Numeric format, with a minus sign for negative amounts, and no currency
indicator.
declarations.title: numeric

declarations.comments:
Numeric format, with a minus sign for negative amounts, and a currency
code.
declarations.title: numericC

declarations.comments:
Accountant format, with negative amounts parenthesized, and no currency
code.
declarations.title: accountant

declarations.comments:
Accountant format, with negative amounts parenthesized, and a currency
code.
declarations.title: accountantC
